Here’s a function signature from a real Angular service:
typescript
addItemToCart(productId: string, quantity: number, price: number): Observable<void>What’s wrong with this? Nothing, at first glance. But consider:

• productId: string — Which kind of ID? Could you accidentally pass a userId here? TypeScript says yes.

• quantity: number — Can it be 0? -1? 0.5? The type doesn't tell you.

• price: number — Dollars? Cents? EUR? GBP? What happens when you add two prices from different currencies?
These are primitive obsession bugs waiting to happen. They’ve already happened in your codebase — you just haven’t found them yet.
typescript
// This compiles with no errors in TypeScript:
const userId = 'user-123';
const orderId = 'order-456';
cartService.addItemToCart(userId, -1, NaN); // ✅ TypeScript is happy. Your runtime is not.Value Objects are the DDD solution. They wrap primitives in domain-meaningful types that validate themselves, express intent, and are impossible to misuse in ways that primitives allow.

What Is a Value Object?
A Value Object has three defining characteristics:

• No identity — Two Value Objects are equal if and only if all their properties are equal. There’s no “ID” — the value is the identity. Money(100, 'EUR') equals any other Money(100, 'EUR').

• Immutable — Once created, a Value Object never changes. Operations return new instances.

• Self-validating — A Value Object that can be constructed is guaranteed to be valid. Invalid values cannot be represented.
Compare this to a primitive: 100 tells you nothing about currency, validity constraints, or intent. Money(100, 'EUR') tells you everything.

Building ShopFlow’s Value Object Library
Let’s build the full set of Value Objects for ShopFlow, starting from the most fundamental.
1. Money — The Most Important Value Object in Any E-Commerce App
typescript
// shared-kernel/money.value-object.tsexport type CurrencyCode = 'EUR' | 'USD' | 'GBP' | 'CHF' | 'JPY';// Currencies that don't use minor units (e.g., JPY has no cents)
const ZERO_DECIMAL_CURRENCIES = new Set<CurrencyCode>(['JPY']);export class Money {
// Store in minor units to avoid floating-point arithmetic errors.
// €10.99 is stored as 1099 (cents).
private readonly _amountInMinorUnits: number;
private readonly _currency: CurrencyCode; private constructor(amountInMinorUnits: number, currency: CurrencyCode) {
if (!Number.isInteger(amountInMinorUnits)) {
throw new Error(
`Money amount must be an integer (minor units). Got: ${amountInMinorUnits}`
);
}
if (amountInMinorUnits < 0) {
throw new Error(`Money amount cannot be negative: ${amountInMinorUnits}`);
}
this._amountInMinorUnits = amountInMinorUnits;
this._currency = currency;
} // --- Factory methods (named constructors) --- static ofMinorUnits(amountInMinorUnits: number, currency: CurrencyCode): Money {
return new Money(amountInMinorUnits, currency);
} static ofMajorUnits(amount: number, currency: CurrencyCode): Money {
if (ZERO_DECIMAL_CURRENCIES.has(currency)) {
return new Money(Math.round(amount), currency);
}
// Round to avoid floating-point: 10.99 * 100 = 1098.9999999... in JS
return new Money(Math.round(amount * 100), currency);
} static zero(currency: CurrencyCode): Money {
return new Money(0, currency);
} // --- Accessors --- get amountInMinorUnits(): number {
return this._amountInMinorUnits;
} get amountInMajorUnits(): number {
if (ZERO_DECIMAL_CURRENCIES.has(this._currency)) {
return this._amountInMinorUnits;
}
return this._amountInMinorUnits / 100;
} get currency(): CurrencyCode {
return this._currency;
} get isZero(): boolean {
return this._amountInMinorUnits === 0;
} // --- Operations (return new instances — immutable) --- add(other: Money): Money {
this.assertSameCurrency(other);
return new Money(this._amountInMinorUnits + other._amountInMinorUnits, this._currency);
} subtract(other: Money): Money {
this.assertSameCurrency(other);
const result = this._amountInMinorUnits - other._amountInMinorUnits;
if (result < 0) {
throw new Error(
`Cannot subtract: result would be negative (${this.format()} - ${other.format()})`
);
}
return new Money(result, this._currency);
} multiply(factor: number): Money {
if (factor < 0) throw new Error(`Money multiplier cannot be negative: ${factor}`);
return new Money(Math.round(this._amountInMinorUnits * factor), this._currency);
} percentage(percent: number): Money {
if (percent < 0 || percent > 100) {
throw new Error(`Percentage must be between 0 and 100: ${percent}`);
}
return new Money(
Math.round(this._amountInMinorUnits * (percent / 100)),
this._currency
);
} // --- Comparison --- equals(other: Money): boolean {
return (
this._amountInMinorUnits === other._amountInMinorUnits &&
this._currency === other._currency
);
} isGreaterThan(other: Money): boolean {
this.assertSameCurrency(other);
return this._amountInMinorUnits > other._amountInMinorUnits;
} isLessThan(other: Money): boolean {
this.assertSameCurrency(other);
return this._amountInMinorUnits < other._amountInMinorUnits;
} // --- Formatting --- format(locale = 'en-US'): string {
return new Intl.NumberFormat(locale, {
style: 'currency',
currency: this._currency,
}).format(this.amountInMajorUnits);
} toString(): string {
return this.format();
} // --- Serialization (for NgRx state — must be plain objects) --- toJSON(): { amountInMinorUnits: number; currency: CurrencyCode } {
return {
amountInMinorUnits: this._amountInMinorUnits,
currency: this._currency,
};
} static fromJSON(json: { amountInMinorUnits: number; currency: CurrencyCode }): Money {
return new Money(json.amountInMinorUnits, json.currency);
} private assertSameCurrency(other: Money): void {
if (this._currency !== other._currency) {
throw new Error(
`Currency mismatch: cannot operate on ${this._currency} and ${other._currency}`
);
}
}
}Now operations are safe and expressive:
typescript
const price = Money.ofMajorUnits(29.99, 'EUR');
const shipping = Money.ofMajorUnits(4.99, 'EUR');
const total = price.add(shipping);
console.log(total.format('de-DE')); // "34,98 €"// ❌ This is a compile error now — can't add EUR to USD
const usdPrice = Money.ofMajorUnits(29.99, 'USD');
// price.add(usdPrice); // ← throws at runtime with a clear message2. Typed ID Value Objects — Preventing ID Confusion
typescript
// shared-kernel/typed-id.value-object.ts// Abstract base — forces every ID to be a distinct type
abstract class TypedId {
private readonly _value: string; constructor(value: string) {
if (!value || value.trim().length === 0) {
throw new Error(`${this.constructor.name} cannot be empty`);
}
this._value = value.trim();
} get value(): string {
return this._value;
} equals(other: this): boolean {
return this._value === other._value;
} toString(): string {
return this._value;
} toJSON(): string {
return this._value;
}
}// Each context gets its own ID type — not interchangeable
export class ProductId extends TypedId {}
export class CartId extends TypedId {}
export class CartItemId extends TypedId {}
export class OrderId extends TypedId {}
export class CustomerId extends TypedId {}
export class CouponId extends TypedId {}// TypeScript now prevents cross-domain ID mixing:
function getCart(cartId: CartId): Observable<Cart> { /* ... */ }const productId = new ProductId('prod-123');
// getCart(productId); // ← TypeScript ERROR: ProductId is not CartId ✅3. Email — With Built-in Validation
typescript
// shared-kernel/email.value-object.tsexport class Email {
private static readonly EMAIL_REGEX = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;
private readonly _value: string; constructor(value: string) {
const normalized = value.trim().toLowerCase();
if (!Email.EMAIL_REGEX.test(normalized)) {
throw new Error(`Invalid email address: "${value}"`);
}
this._value = normalized;
} get value(): string {
return this._value;
} get domain(): string {
return this._value.split('@')[1];
} equals(other: Email): boolean {
return this._value === other._value;
} toString(): string {
return this._value;
}
}4. Quantity — With Business Rules Built In
typescript
// shared-kernel/quantity.value-object.tsexport class Quantity {
private static readonly MAX_PER_CART_ITEM = 99;
private readonly _value: number; constructor(value: number) {
if (!Number.isInteger(value)) {
throw new Error(`Quantity must be an integer: ${value}`);
}
if (value < 1) {
throw new Error(`Quantity must be at least 1: ${value}`);
}
if (value > Quantity.MAX_PER_CART_ITEM) {
throw new Error(
`Quantity cannot exceed ${Quantity.MAX_PER_CART_ITEM}: ${value}`
);
}
this._value = value;
} get value(): number {
return this._value;
} increment(): Quantity {
return new Quantity(this._value + 1);
} decrement(): Quantity {
if (this._value === 1) {
throw new Error('Cannot decrement quantity below 1');
}
return new Quantity(this._value - 1);
} add(other: Quantity): Quantity {
return new Quantity(this._value + other._value);
} equals(other: Quantity): boolean {
return this._value === other._value;
} toString(): string {
return String(this._value);
}
}5. Address — A Value Object with Multiple Fields
typescript
// shared-kernel/address.value-object.tsexport interface AddressProps {
street: string;
city: string;
postcode: string;
countryCode: string; // ISO 3166-1 alpha-2
state?: string;
}export class Address {
readonly street: string;
readonly city: string;
readonly postcode: string;
readonly countryCode: string;
readonly state: string | undefined; constructor(props: AddressProps) {
if (!props.street.trim()) throw new Error('Street is required');
if (!props.city.trim()) throw new Error('City is required');
if (!props.postcode.trim()) throw new Error('Postcode is required');
if (props.countryCode.length !== 2) {
throw new Error(`Invalid country code: ${props.countryCode}`);
} this.street = props.street.trim();
this.city = props.city.trim();
this.postcode = props.postcode.trim().toUpperCase();
this.countryCode = props.countryCode.toUpperCase();
this.state = props.state?.trim();
} get oneLiner(): string {
const parts = [this.street, this.city, this.postcode, this.countryCode];
if (this.state) parts.splice(2, 0, this.state);
return parts.join(', ');
} withStreet(newStreet: string): Address {
return new Address({ ...this, street: newStreet });
} equals(other: Address): boolean {
return (
this.street === other.street &&
this.city === other.city &&
this.postcode === other.postcode &&
this.countryCode === other.countryCode &&
this.state === other.state
);
}
}
Using Value Objects in Angular
In Reactive Forms
The tricky part: reactive form controls work with primitive values. Value Objects need to be constructed from form data:
typescript
// checkout/presentation/address-form/address-form.component.ts
@Component({
selector: 'shopflow-address-form',
template: `
<form [formGroup]="form">
<input formControlName="street" placeholder="Street address" />
<input formControlName="city" placeholder="City" />
<input formControlName="postcode" placeholder="Postcode" />
<select formControlName="countryCode">
<option value="DE">Germany</option>
<option value="FR">France</option>
<option value="GB">United Kingdom</option>
</select>
<p class="error" *ngIf="addressError">{{ addressError }}</p>
</form>
`
})
export class AddressFormComponent {
form = this.fb.group({
street: ['', Validators.required],
city: ['', Validators.required],
postcode: ['', Validators.required],
countryCode: ['DE', Validators.required],
}); addressError: string | null = null; constructor(private fb: FormBuilder) {} // Convert form value to Value Object — validation happens here
buildAddress(): Address | null {
if (this.form.invalid) return null; try {
const address = new Address(this.form.value as AddressProps);
this.addressError = null;
return address;
} catch (error: unknown) {
// Value Object validation provides the error message
this.addressError = error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Invalid address';
return null;
}
}
}
